[1
Date: 29 Sep 2000 08:02:25 -0400
From: Ron Gold <rongold@attcanada.ca>

Re: Enterovirus interference: Request for Information
------------------------------------------------------
In the comment to the preceding post the Moderator [CP stated that: "Some
years ago it was an accepted view that live poliovirus vaccines would be
ineffective in underdeveloped countries due to the prevalence of unrelated
enterovirus infections and consequent enteroviral interference. The success
of the WHO polio eradication programme has nullified this hypothesis".
On the contrary, The WHO polio eradication program has done absolutely
nothing to nullify the hypothesis of interference. The program requires the
use of National Immunization Days (NID) in which all children under 5 years
of age are immunized on the same day (or same weekend) with a second NID
4-8 weeks later. NIDs are used, as initially demonstrated in trials in
Mexico by Dr. Sabin, in order to ensure that oral poliovirus vaccine
strains saturate the community, interrupt transmission of other enteric
viruses, and overcome interference from other enteric viruses. Routine
immunization based on age of child, i.e., at 2, 4, 6 months, as in the EPI
program has never been successful in interrupting wild polio transmission
in underdeveloped countries when used on its own.
--
Ron Gold
<rongold@attcanada.ca>
